<nyne-vfs>

This codebase is mounted through **nyne**, a FUSE virtual filesystem. Every source file has an `@/` companion namespace directory exposing decomposed symbols, LSP intelligence, and git history. **All `@/` paths are real files** — they work with the Read tool, Edit tool, Write tool, Bash commands (`cat`, `echo >`, `ls`, `mv`, `rmdir`), and shell pipes.

The nyne VFS is designed for efficient, precise code traversal, access and modification, with minimal token consumption. Use the nyne VFS for all code exploration, analysis, and edits — avoid direct file access when `@/` paths are available.

## nyne VFS Tool Rules and Best Practices

- **Read** VFS paths with the **Read tool**. **Edit** with the **Edit tool** (`old_string`/`new_string`). Use **Bash** for structural ops (`mv`, `rmdir`, `rm`), single-value writes (`echo >`), and shell pipelines. **Do not use `sed -i`** — it creates a temp file + rename, which FUSE doesn't support.
- **Avoid using Edit on raw source files** — always target `@/` symbol bodies instead. Edit on a symbol body only sends the diff, not the full file.
- **Read before Edit — always.** The Edit tool requires a prior Read (via the Read tool) of the same file. `cat` via Bash does NOT satisfy this. After modifying a file via Bash (`echo >`, `rmdir`, batch edit `rm`), you must Read the file again before using Edit on it.
- **Never read raw source files** when VFS paths exist. Always Read `OVERVIEW.md` first, then specific symbol bodies.
- **Start with `OVERVIEW.md`** to discover exact symbol names before accessing them.
- **Use VFS analysis tools, not Grep**, for call-graph questions: `CALLERS.md` shows blast radius, `DEPS.md` for tracing callees, `REFERENCES.md` before renaming/deleting. These targeted, token-optimized files replace grep-for-usage workflows.
- **Check `actions/`** before any refactoring task — an LSP code action `.diff` may already exist to execute the refactoring.
- **Writes re-parse the file.** After any write to a `@/` path, symbol names may change (disambiguators added/removed, symbols deleted, nesting shifted). Re-read `OVERVIEW.md` or `ls symbols/` before accessing other symbols in the same file.
- **Use batch edit staging for multi-symbol changes.** When changing multiple symbols in the same file, or when coordinating changes across files, stage via `edit/` and apply atomically with `rm @/edit/staged.diff`. Safe (tree-sitter validated) and cheap (one atomic write). Returns an error if validation fails.

Use the Read tool for `@/` reads. When you have a line number (from errors, grep, OVERVIEW), use `/symbols/at-line/<line>` — it's a symlink to the containing symbol's body and can be read and and modified directly.

Uppercased files (`OVERVIEW.md`, `CALLERS.md`, etc.) are read-only and optimized for token efficient lookup and exploration.

Lowercased files and directories (`body.{{ ext }}`, `docstring.txt`, etc.) are virtual files representing "slices" of a source code file: symbol bodies, docstrings, decorators, import sections, and more. These are all regular editable files; you can use your normal Read, Edit and Write tools on these files directly.

| What | Path |
|-|-|
| File overview (metadata + symbols + access guide) | Read `file.{{ ext }}@/OVERVIEW.md` |
| Directory overview | Read `src/module@/OVERVIEW.md` |
| Symbol body | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/body.{{ ext }}` |
| Signature only | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/signature.{{ ext }}` |
| Symbol docstring | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/docstring.txt` |
| File/module docstring | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/docstring.txt` |
| Decorators/attrs | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/decorators.{{ ext }}` |
| Import block | Read/Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}` |
| Generated docs | Read `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/DOC.md` |

### Reading and Exploring

Read the symbol at line 42 (follows symlink → body):

    Read `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42`

Directly edit a symbol at a known line:

    Read → Edit `file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42`

    Note: at-line is symlinked directly to the symbol body → `../Foo~Impl@/process@/body.{{ ext }}`

Insert code at known location:

    echo 'fn foo() { }' >> file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10

Line range reads (escape hatch — prefer symbol-targeted access):

    Read `file.{{ ext }}@/lines` (full file)
    Read `file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10-20` (range)

Delete a line range:

    rm file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10-20

List symbols by kind:

    ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/fn/

### Writing

Prefer the Edit tool for targeted changes in known files:

    Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }} ← Read first
    Edit file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }} ← old_string/new_string

Bash examples for single-value writes and structural operations:

```bash
# Add an import
echo 'use std::collections::HashMap;' >>file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}

# Replace a function signature
echo 'fn process(input: &str, opts: Options) -> Result<()>' \
    >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/signature.{{ ext }}

# Add a decorator/attribute
echo '#[instrument]' >>file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/decorators.{{ ext }}

# Delete a symbol (removes the entire body, docstring, decorators, etc.)
rmdir file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_helper@/
```

All writes to `@/` paths are tree-sitter validated and safe. Invalid syntax returns an error, not a broken file.

## Batch Edit Staging

Batch Edit is the go-to for multi-step edits: stage multiple changes across symbols and files, then apply all changes atomically. Prefer this over sequential direct writes when changing multiple symbols. Apply returns an error if validation fails — no need to preview first.

| Scenario | Approach |
|-|-|
| Change 1 symbol | Edit tool (read first, then old_string/new_string) |
| Change 2+ symbols in one file | Batch edit staging |
| Coordinated changes across files | Batch edit staging (cross-file atomic) |
| Delete multiple symbols | Batch edit staging |

```bash
# 1. Stage edits (write to any symbol's edit/ namespace)
echo 'fn new_impl(){}' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/edit/replace # replace entire body
echo 'fn helper(){}' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Bar@/edit/insert-after # insert after body
echo '/// docs' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Baz@/edit/insert-before # insert before body
echo 1 >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Old@/edit/delete # delete entire symbol
echo 'fn method(){}' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/MyImpl@/edit/append # append to body

# 2. Apply all staged edits atomically (returns error if tree-sitter validation fails)
rm @/edit/staged.diff

# Or clear without applying (truncate)
> @/edit/staged.diff
```

## Refactoring

Diff files (code actions, renames) are applied by deleting them (`rm`). Preview with `cat`, apply with `rm`.

```bash
# LSP rename — immediate, project-wide, always use this instead of manual renames across files
mv file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/ file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/new_name@/

# Optional: Preview rename first, then apply
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/rename/new_name.diff
rm file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/rename/new_name.diff

# List available LSP code actions
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/

# Preview a code action, then apply
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/01-fix.diff
rm file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/01-fix.diff
```

## Analysis

| What | When to use | Path |
|-|-|-|
| Callers (incoming) | Before changing signature or behavior — shows who will break | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/CALLERS.md` |
| Dependencies (outgoing) | Tracing what a function calls — don't Grep for callees | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/DEPS.md` |
| All references | Before renaming, moving, or deleting — every usage site | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/REFERENCES.md` |
| Trait implementations | Working with a trait — all concrete impls | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/MyTrait@/IMPLEMENTATION.md` |
| Project TODOs | Scanning for outstanding work | `Read @/todo/TODO.md` |

Note: Symlinks in `callers/`, `deps/`, `references/`, `implementation/` are shortcuts to related symbols' `@/` directories — follow to read, edit, and inspect linked symbols directly.

## Symbol Naming

`OVERVIEW.md` lists exact symbol names. When a name ends with `@/`, it's a nyne namespace — nested symbols are **direct children** (no intermediate `symbols/` directory):

```
OVERVIEW shows: MyImpl@/  (Impl, with nested: process@/, validate@/)
Full path:      file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/MyImpl@/process@/body.{{ ext }}
```

- Top-level: `symbols/my_function@/body.{{ ext }}`
- Trait/interface impls: `symbols/Display_for_Foo@/body.{{ ext }}`
- Name collisions: `symbols/Foo~Struct@/body.{{ ext }}`, `symbols/Foo~Fn@/body.{{ ext }}`
- Nested (impl methods): `symbols/Foo~Impl@/new@/body.{{ ext }}`

When names are ambiguous, `ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/` shows the exact filesystem entries.

